{{Sections|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Max Kohnstamm | image = Max Kohnstamm.JPG | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1914|5|22}} | birth_place = [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|2010|10|20|1914|5|22}} | death_place = Amsterdam, Netherlands | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = historian and diplomat | occupation = }} '''Max Kohnstamm''' (22 May 1914 – 20 October 2010) was a Dutch historian and diplomat.
Max Kohnstamm was born in Amsterdam, Netherlands, the son of [[Philip Kohnstamm]], a physicist, philosopher and pedagogue of Jewish-German origin. His father was married to one of the daughters of [[Jean Baptiste August Kessler]], who helped create the company now known as [[Royal Dutch Shell]]; one of his uncles was [[Geldolph Adriaan Kessler]], who helped create the Dutch steel industry. During World War II, Kohnstamm and Kessler were both held hostage by the Germans along with other prominent Dutchmen at camp [[Gymnasium Beekvliet|Beekvliet]] in [[Sint-Michielsgestel]]; they became quite close there despite the difference in age.<ref>{{Harvnb|de Clercq|2010|p=105}}</ref> He was one of the founding fathers of the European Union and played a major part in the 1950s in the development European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC) and then of the European Economic Communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/18/max-kohnstamm-obituary|title=Max Kohnstamm obituary|first=John|last=Palmer|date=18 November 2010|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>
He was educated at [[University of Amsterdam|Amsterdam University]], where he studied Modern History, before taking up a fellowship at [[American University]], [[Washington, D.C.]]. During 1938 and 1939 he travelled through the United States as part of his studies. His correspondence with his father during this period discussed his impressions of the United States and his concerns with the looming war.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kohnstamm | first = Dolph (Editor) | title = Still No War: Correspondence Between Two Dutchmen - son Max and father, Philip Kohnstamm | publisher = Athena Press | year = 2003 | location = London }}</ref>
He was private secretary to [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands]] from 1945 to 1948, then served with the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Netherlands)|Netherlands Foreign Office]] from 1948 to 1952. During this time he was head of its German Bureau and Director of European Affairs. He was Vice President of the Netherlands' [[Schuman Declaration|Schuman Plan]] delegation in 1950, serving as Secretary to the [[High Authority of the European Coal and Steel Community]] from 1952 to 1956. He was Vice President of the Action Committee for the United States of Europe from 1956. He was President of the [[European University Institute]] in [[Florence]]. He was Chairman of the [[Trilateral Commission]] in Europe.
He was a member of the [[Club of Rome]] global think-tank, being one of the six member "inner group" at the time its influential work the ''Limits to Growth'' was published.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubofrome.ro/ |title=Romanian Association for the Club of Rome}}</ref>
He was a former member of the Steering Committee of the [[Bilderberg Group]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |title=Bilderberg Meetings, Former Steering Committee Members |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202095633/http://www.bilderbergmeetings.org/former-steering-committee-members.html |archivedate=2014-02-02 |df= }}</ref>
He was the Founding European Chairman of the [[Trilateral Commission]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trilateral.org/download/file/Max%20Kohnstamm%201914-2010.pdf |title=In Memoriam, Trilateral Commission}}</ref>
In 2004, Kohnstamm was awarded the 'Freedom from Fear' [[Four Freedoms Award]] by the Roosevelt Stichting.
He died in Amsterdam, aged 96.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/nov/18/max-kohnstamm-obituary|title=Max Kohnstamm obituary|first=John|last=Palmer|date=18 November 2010|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref>
