{{Notability|date=September 2018}}

{{Nihongo|'''Takuya Iwasaki'''|岩崎 卓也|Iwasaki Takuya|July 9, 1929 – February 4, 2018}} was a Japanese archaeologist.

==Biography==
He was an expert in the Neolithic and early period of the Middle East and has conducted much research into sites in countries like Syria and Iran.<ref>{{cite book|last=Iwasaki|first=Takuya|author2=恵子·石田|title=Tell Mastuma: An Iron Age Settlement in Northwest Syria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qu4kYAAACAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Ancient Orient Museum|isbn=978-4-906127-03-0}}</ref><ref name="MatthewsNashli2013">{{cite book|last1=Matthews|first1=Roger|last2=Nashli|first2=Hassan Fazeli|title=The Neolithisation of Iran|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SuM7BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA201|date=11 December 2013|publisher=Oxbow Books|isbn=978-1-78297-191-7|page=201}}</ref> Iwasaki was a Professor at the [[University of Tsukuba]]. Formally, from 1990, in coordination with the university, he conducted extensive field work in the [[Rouj Basin]] of northwest Syria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.histanth.tsukuba.ac.jp/tap/elrouj/WWW/rouj/intro.html|title=Introduction|publisher=Histanth.tsukuba.ac.jp|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref> 

Along with Akira Tsuneki, he co-wrote ''Archaeology of the Rouj Basin''. He was involved with the Tokyo Women's College of Home Economics, and directed the [[Matsudo|Matsudo City Museum]] from 2006–10. He was a member of the Japan Science Council. He died on February 4, 2018 at the age of 88.<ref>[https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO26571490W8A200C1CC0000/ 岩崎卓也氏が死去　元日本考古学協会会長] {{ja icon}}</ref>

